  "text": "In the past 2 decades, Tg assays have shown increased diagnostic accuracy and ever improving functional sensitivity. Still, current guidelines suggest that patients thought to be free of disease undergo stimulated serum Tg (stim-Tg) testing about 1 yr after initial RRA to optimize diagnostic accuracy [recommendation 45a [CITATION_1] ]. Several publications in recent years have suggested that the negative predictive value when this first stim-Tg is undetectable, or less than 1 ng/ml, is so high that future stim-Tg testing is of limited value (4 -6) . Indeed, the American Thyroid Association guidelines state that the timing or necessity of further stim-Tg testing is uncertain, and recommend follow-up based primarily on yearly clinical examination and Tg measurements on thyroid hormone replacement (Tg-on) [recommendation 45b [CITATION_2] ].",
